KW  - cold turkey
KW  - disinflation
KW  - gradualism
KW  - inflation inertia
KW  - level-k
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-2879
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jmcb.12904
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - Abstract It is widely believed that inflation inertia varies with the policy pursued. In a novel experiment, price setters determine inflation rates and react to a central bank's indicator, which is implemented exogenously either as cold turkey or gradual disinflation. In a third treatment, subjects in the role of a central banker set the indicator endogenously, potentially reducing inertia by signaling to be a tough central banker. I find inertia to be structurally stable and invariant to policies. The data can be organized by a model of level- thinking, which shows that cold turkey improves only a few subjects' adjustment while leaving many behind.
ER  - 

